Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Pour a good glug of @oil{} into a #baking tray{} (to completely cover the bottom) and pop into your oven. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide chips (no need to peel). Pour the boiling water into a large #saucepan{} on high heat with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook until the edges have softened when you poke them with a knife, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Meanwhile, zest and halve the @lemon{1/2}. Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(finely chopped) (stalks and all) and put half in a medium #bowl{} with the lemon zest. Add the @panko breadcrumbs{25%g} and @oil{} for the breadcrumbs. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} then set aside. Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{} and pop back into the pan. Season with salt and sprinkle on the @plain flour{8%g}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potatoes. Take your hot baking tray out of the oven and carefully transfer your potatoes into it in a single layer, turning in the oil. Roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}, turning halfway through.

In the meantime, finely chop the @capers{30%g}. Put into a small bowl and add the remaining parsley and three quarters of the @mayonnaise{2}. Mix together, then season to taste with salt, pepper and lemon juice. Cut any remaining lemon into wedges.

Lay the @sea bass fillets{2}, skin-side down, onto a baking tray lined with #baking paper{}. Divide and spread the remaining mayonnaise over the top of the fish. Spoon the breadcrumb mixture on top. Press it down with a #spoon{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, then set aside until the chips are halfway through cooking. Then, bake the fish on the middle shelf of the oven until golden, ~{10-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw fish. The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and finely chopped) into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Pick the @mint{1/2}(roughly chopped) leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). When roughly 5 mins of cooking time remain, add the @unsalted butter{30%g} to a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. When the butter has melted, add the shallot and cook until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add the garlic and @peas{120%g}, then stir-fry for ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper, stir through the mint, then take off the heat.

When everything is ready, serve the fish with the chips and buttery minted peas alongside. Sprinkle the @cider vinegar{15%ml} over the chips and season with more @salt{} if you'd like. Serve with a dollop of @tartare sauce{} and the lemon wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!